Catch raw hrefs as bad, warn unless wrapped in a safe methodAdd concept of a safe-ening method to mark hrefs as safennFeature:nWarn when using unsafe hrefs.  This is a very specific case that as of now produces a ton of noise.  This came out of an xss vuln where the value was escaped but still vulnerable.nnlink_to 'asdf', h(@scary)nnwherenn@scary = 'javascript:alert(1)'nnornn@scary = 'data:  # http://palpapers.plynt.com/issues/2010Oct/bypass-xss-filters/nnThis branch accomplishes slightly intelligent warnings by adding a new command line option to declare methods that make a string URL safe (unless there is already a standard one out there).  e.g.:nn$ brakeman . --url-safe-methods ensure_valid_protocol!nnlink_to 'asdf', ensure_valid_protocol!(@scary, :javascript)n

Code Climate engine: fix `include_paths` when using custom app pathBrakeman (very reasonably) expects the `only_files` options to benrelative to the `app_path` option. The support that was added to thenCode Climate engine for a custom `app_path` option did not taken`include_paths` into account, so the normal result of using a customn`app_path` would have ended up being that *nothing* would get analyzed:nbecause with a custom `app_path` of, say, `foo`, an include path mightninclude something like `foo/bar` when it needs to be adjusted to justn`bar`.nnThe fix here is to strip the `app_path` prefix from all matchingn`include_paths`, and drop non-matching `include_paths` entirely.n

Deprecate safe_level of ERB.new in Ruby 2.6This PR suppresses the following warnings when using Ruby 2.6.0-dev.nn```consolen% ruby -vnruby 2.6.0dev (2018-05-22 trunk 63488) [x86_64-darwin17]n%RUBYOPT='-w' bundle exec raken(snip)n/Users/koic/src/github.com/presidentbeef/brakeman/lib/brakeman/parsers/template_parser.rb:61:nwarning: Passing safe_level with the 2nd argument of ERB.new is deprecated.nDo not use it, and specify other arguments as keyword arguments.n/Users/koic/src/github.com/presidentbeef/brakeman/lib/brakeman/parsers/template_parser.rb:61:nwarning: Passing trim_mode with the 3rd argument of ERB.new is deprecated.nUse keyword argument like ERB.new(str, trim_mode: ...) instead.n```nnThe interface of `ERB.new` will change from Ruby 2.6.nn> Add :trim_mode and :eoutvar keyword arguments to ERB.new.n> Now non-keyword arguments other than first one are softly deprecatedn> and will be removed when Ruby 2.5 becomes EOL. [Feature #14256]nnhttps://github.com/ruby/ruby/blob/2311087/NEWS#stdlib-updates-outstanding-ones-onlynnThis PR uses `ERB.instance_method(:initialize).parameters.assoc(:key)`nto switch `ERB.new` interface. Because Brakeman supports multiple Rubynversions, it need to use the appropriate interface. This approach isnbuilt into Ruby.nhttps://github.com/ruby/ruby/commit/3406c5dn
